---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Understanding Quadratic Equations - Richad's Blog" description="A comprehensive guide to solving quadratic equations using different methods">
	<article class="blog-post">
		<header class="post-header">
			<div class="post-meta">
				<span class="post-category">Algebra</span>
				<span class="post-date">December 10, 2024</span>
			</div>
			<h1 class="post-title">Understanding Quadratic Equations</h1>
			<p class="post-subtitle">A comprehensive guide to solving quadratic equations using different methods</p>
			<div class="post-tags">
				<span class="tag">Quadratics</span>
				<span class="tag">Problem Solving</span>
				<span class="tag">Algebra</span>
			</div>
		</header>

		<div class="post-content">
			<section class="content-section">
				<h2>What is a Quadratic Equation?</h2>
				<p>
					A quadratic equation is a polynomial equation of degree 2, which means the highest power of the variable is 2. 
					The standard form of a quadratic equation is:
				</p>
				<div class="equation-block">
					<code>ax² + bx + c = 0</code>
				</div>
				<p>
					Where <strong>a</strong>, <strong>b</strong>, and <strong>c</strong> are constants, and <strong>a ≠ 0</strong>. 
					If a = 0, then the equation becomes linear, not quadratic!
				</p>
			</section>

			<section class="content-section">
				<h2>Method 1: Factoring</h2>
				<p>
					Factoring is often the quickest method when the quadratic can be easily factored. Let's look at an example:
				</p>
				<div class="example-box">
					<h3>Example: x² + 5x + 6 = 0</h3>
					<div class="solution-steps">
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Step 1:</strong> Find two numbers that multiply to give 6 and add to give 5.
							<br>Those numbers are 2 and 3 (since 2 × 3 = 6 and 2 + 3 = 5).
						</div>
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Step 2:</strong> Factor the equation: (x + 2)(x + 3) = 0
						</div>
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Step 3:</strong> Set each factor equal to zero:
							<br>x + 2 = 0  →  x = -2
							<br>x + 3 = 0  →  x = -3
						</div>
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Solution:</strong> x = -2 or x = -3
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="content-section">
				<h2>Method 2: Completing the Square</h2>
				<p>
					This method involves manipulating the equation to create a perfect square trinomial. 
					It's especially useful when factoring isn't straightforward.
				</p>
				<div class="example-box">
					<h3>Example: x² + 6x + 5 = 0</h3>
					<div class="solution-steps">
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Step 1:</strong> Move the constant to the right side: x² + 6x = -5
						</div>
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Step 2:</strong> Take half of the coefficient of x and square it: (6/2)² = 9
						</div>
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Step 3:</strong> Add this to both sides: x² + 6x + 9 = -5 + 9 = 4
						</div>
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Step 4:</strong> Factor the left side: (x + 3)² = 4
						</div>
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Step 5:</strong> Take the square root: x + 3 = ±2
						</div>
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Solution:</strong> x = -3 + 2 = -1 or x = -3 - 2 = -5
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="content-section">
				<h2>Method 3: The Quadratic Formula</h2>
				<p>
					The quadratic formula is the most reliable method and works for any quadratic equation. 
					It's derived from completing the square on the general form:
				</p>
				<div class="equation-block">
					<code>x = (-b ± √(b² - 4ac)) / (2a)</code>
				</div>
				<div class="example-box">
					<h3>Example: 2x² + 7x + 3 = 0</h3>
					<div class="solution-steps">
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Step 1:</strong> Identify a = 2, b = 7, c = 3
						</div>
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Step 2:</strong> Calculate the discriminant: b² - 4ac = 49 - 24 = 25
						</div>
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Step 3:</strong> Apply the formula:
							<br>x = (-7 ± √25) / (2×2) = (-7 ± 5) / 4
						</div>
						<div class="step">
							<strong>Solution:</strong> x = (-7 + 5)/4 = -1/2 or x = (-7 - 5)/4 = -3
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="content-section">
				<h2>The Discriminant: What It Tells Us</h2>
				<p>
					The discriminant (b² - 4ac) tells us about the nature of the solutions:
				</p>
				<ul class="info-list">
					<li><strong>If b² - 4ac > 0:</strong> Two distinct real solutions</li>
					<li><strong>If b² - 4ac = 0:</strong> One repeated real solution</li>
					<li><strong>If b² - 4ac < 0:</strong> No real solutions (two complex solutions)</li>
				</ul>
			</section>

			<section class="content-section">
				<h2>When to Use Each Method</h2>
				<div class="method-guide">
					<div class="method-card">
						<h3>Factoring</h3>
						<p>Use when the equation factors easily. Quick and elegant when it works!</p>
					</div>
					<div class="method-card">
						<h3>Completing the Square</h3>
						<p>Great for understanding the vertex form and when you need exact answers.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="method-card">
						<h3>Quadratic Formula</h3>
						<p>Always works! Use when other methods are difficult or impossible.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="content-section">
				<h2>Practice Problems</h2>
				<p>Try solving these quadratic equations using different methods:</p>
				<ol class="practice-list">
					<li>x² - 4x + 3 = 0</li>
					<li>x² + 8x + 16 = 0</li>
					<li>3x² - 2x - 1 = 0</li>
					<li>x² + 2x + 5 = 0</li>
				</ol>
				<p class="practice-note">
					<strong>Hint:</strong> Try factoring first, then use other methods if needed. 
					Check your answers by substituting back into the original equation!
				</p>
			</section>
		</div>

		<footer class="post-footer">
			<div class="post-navigation">
				<a href="/blog" class="nav-link">← Back to Blog</a>
				<a href="/blog/prime-numbers" class="nav-link">Next Post: Prime Numbers →</a>
			</div>
		</footer>
	</article>
</Layout>

